	"conclusion": "For OpenAI, the career page partially precedes Glassdoor: 28% of matched jobs (24/87) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 118 days (median: 75 days). An additional 519 jobs (86% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Glassdoor at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "Analysis of job posting data reveals a clear and substantial lead for company career pages over Glassdoor in publishing new job opportunities. Out of 87 jobs matched across both platforms, 24 (28%) first appeared on the company's dedicated career page. This initial appearance on career pages occurred with an average lag of 118 days and a median lag of 75 days before the postings were observed on Glassdoor. Furthermore, a significant majority of unique job postings, 519 out of 606 (85.6%), were exclusively found on company career pages within the analysis period and never detected on Glassdoor, underscoring the limited coverage of Glassdoor for this dataset. Conversely, 61 jobs appeared first on Glassdoor, and 2 were observed on the same day.\n\nDelving into the lag distribution, it becomes evident that career pages offer more than just a marginal head start. While a few jobs registered relatively short delays, with 3 appearing 1–3 days and another 3 within 8–14 days ahead of Glassdoor, a substantial portion experienced much longer lags. For instance, 5 jobs showed a lead of 61–90 days, and the largest category, comprising 9 jobs, indicated career page appearances 90 or more days before Glassdoor. Notable examples include \"Software Engineer, Data Infrastructure\" which appeared on the career page a staggering 476 days prior to Glassdoor, and \"Software Engineer, Real Time\" with a 463-day lead, illustrating that for a considerable number of roles, the early advantage can span many months.\n\nIt is crucial to acknowledge several caveats when interpreting these findings. The disparity in snapshot frequency is a primary limitation; 200 career page snapshots were processed compared to only 6 for Glassdoor across the analysis period (2024-01-01 to 2026-04-01). This significantly lower sampling rate for Glassdoor means its \"first appearance\" date might be an underestimate, potentially inflating the observed lags or missing jobs entirely that were briefly posted. Therefore, while the trend is robust, the exact magnitude of the average and median lags could be influenced by the infrequent Glassdoor data capture.\n\nGiven these insights, job seekers are strongly advised to prioritize monitoring company career pages directly. By doing so, candidates can gain a substantial competitive advantage, often seeing job postings weeks to several months before they appear on aggregation sites like Glassdoor. Moreover, this direct approach is essential for accessing a significant volume of jobs that may never be syndicated to third-party platforms, thus broadening the scope of available opportunities beyond what is typically visible through general job search engines.",
	"geminiAvailable": true
